Which of these bothers your skin the most? Winter ash be on some next level ish so we have to be careful, y’all. Dry skin can be more prone to other skin issues—as if being dry wasn’t enough. But here are some solutions:

1. Itchy Fabrics. Try to avoid them if possible—but if you can’t, at least try to have a smoother fabric like satin, silk, or cotton as a buffer between your skin.

2. Indoor heating. Now before y’all try to excuse me of saying you can’t put the heat on, REAAAAAD 🤣 Indoor heating can be SUPER drying on the skin—and if you have sinus issues like me, that mess will jack up your whole system. Wake up with your throat on FIYAH 😩

A humidifier is a great tool to have—even in the summer because air conditioning can also be drying.

You can also try to turn the heat temp down if you can. I personally cannot sleep with the heat on because I will wake up with my sinuses DRIED TF OUT even with the humidifier 🥵 So instead I layer up and use an electric blanket with an auto shut-off option. I also put some Aquaphor around my nose to prevent my nose from drying out.

3. Y’all already know hot water makes dry skin WORSE, but y’all must love injuring your skin talmbout you’ll just apply more butters 🤣 I’ll let y’all work that out in therapy. For the rest of you who prefer un-singed skin, turn that water temp down.

4. Now if you follow the first three steps, you will probably not be itchy so you won’t need to scratch. I speak from being a previous offender. I used to be itchy DINNAMUG, but once I did the tips in this post, I’m FREEEEEE.

BUT, if you are doing all of these and still having issues, bring it up with your doctor. You might have a condition that requires more treatment.

Have you ever tried an overnight hydrating mask? They’re dope especially this time of year and yes, even if you have oily skin like me!

My long time friend @thisthatbeauty just launched a trio of masks and my fave so far is the @getphoebeskin Stay Chill Mask! I like to leave this on overnight after I layer up on hydration (you don’t HAVE to use a toner and/or essence nor do you have to use $$$ ones like the ones I’m using, but I’m just using what I use here lol). Stay Chill got that sauce though because it helps to soothe skin that’s been wildin out or stressed due to this dry AF season. 

You can either leave it on overnight like me OR tissue or rinse it off after ten minutes. I use this whenever I feel like my skin can use some extra TLC.

You can grab @getphoebeskin at @luxuriouswellniss (both Black woman owned businesses ✊🏿) via the link in @getphoebeskin’s bio. Tell ‘em I sent ya 😝

What’s the most RIDICULOUS skincare or makeup product you actually love? 

For me it’s this @charlottetilburyskincare Cryo Recovery Mask. It’s very much giving “I ate his liver with fava beans and a nice Chianti” but it’s sooo relaxing 😝

Were you doing this? Some things to look for in a moisturizer for the winter:

⏺️ FATTY ACID OILS: like sunflower seed oil, rosehip oil, safflower seed oil, etc. These can help improve the skin’s barrier which can help fight dry, flaky skin and hyperpigmentation 

@dralexisstephens has a great Youtube video on this called “Best Moisturizers for Hyperpigmentation” if you want to learn more

The moisturizer in this video is by my homie’s brand @nicholeavonie

 I also have drugstore options already on my page—and more coming soon if you want more “bougie” options 😝

⏺️ GLYCERIN: helps draw moisture to the skin

⏺️ HYALURONIC ACID: helps draw moisture to the skin

⏺️ CERAMIDES: helps retain moisture

⏺️ SHEA BUTTER: helps prevent moisture loss

And folks spread misinformation about it all the time, but good ole PETROLEUM JELLY is amazing for preventing water loss. You can apply it to damp skin—you might want to cover the skin so you’re not greasing up your whole house 😩

But always apply moisturizer while your skin is still a little damp 💦

If you have very dry and/or sensitive skin, consider looking into fragrance-free options. 

For *some* people, fragrance can be an irritating trigger that can make the skin itchier and drier.

Which moisturizer are you using right now in the winter? These are just a few examples (all linked in my bio), but if you want to find the best moisturizer for your skin during the winter, here’s what to look for…

⏺️ You may not even have to look far—your favorite brand may make a “heavier” moisturizer that you can use in the winter

⏺️ Ingredients like ceramides, fatty acid oils (ie safflower seed oil, sunflower seed oil, olive oil, etc) help to repair and protect the skin barrier which helps to lessen water loss from the skin. Basically, less dry face 💪🏿 

All of the moisturizers except for the Olay Hyaluronic Peptide24 contain these ingredients. That one is a gel cream moisturizer that hydrates and moisturizes really well yet feels extremely lightweight. This is nice to try on days when it’s not that cold or if it just doesn’t get super cold where you live. It’s also nice for much warmer temps.

Keep in mind that the weather can be tricky—for example, one day it can be below freezing here in NYC and the next it’s 55 degrees or warmer 🥵. I have to check the weather not only to make sure I wear the right clothes, but also the right moisturizer. Keep the weather where you live in mind as that affects your skin.

Most of these moisturizers can work on all skin types (yes, including oily) but it depends on how cold it gets where you live and of course your personal preference, budget, etc.

WHAT DO THE CHILL FACTORS MEAN?
Basically the more 🥶 the colder it is outside. I tried to simplify the Reel as much as possible.

🔥 If you have dry skin, layering might be key for you. Apply your hydrating toner/essence/serum after cleansing while skin is still a little damp and then apply your moisturizer. You could also apply a facial oil on top of your moisturizer. There are Reels on layering hydration on my page—just scroll back 😉

Which one of these causes YOUR acne? For me definitely hormones 😩 Here are some tips for each possible cause:

‼️ KEEP A SKIN DIARY! Track what you put on your skin or use near your skin (ie hair products, detergents, fabrics, fragrances, etc), medications, your feelings, your cycle, what you eat, etc and how your skin reacts to it. Take pictures of your skin—this also helps you see progress 💪🏿 Doing this can help you try to figure out potential triggers.

1. PRODUCTS: it’s a great practice to patch test any products you’ve never tried before and SLOWLY introduce them into your routine.

If you wash your hair in the shower, it’s a good idea to cleanse your face after using your hair products.

Also note any other products that come in contact with your skin like detergents, cleaning products, things you cook with, etc.

2. HORMONES. This can be tricky to combat, but at least knowing when your cycle is approaching may help you remember to get some acne products in your stash.

Best bet though is to see your doctor to check for any possible conditions that could be controlled and in turn could control your acne.

3. STRESS. I highly recommend seeing a therapist to help with this. Exercise can also help alleviate some stress.

4. DIET. Certain foods can possibly trigger acne for some people. This doesn’t necessarily mean you need to cut out certain foods completely, but being more aware and eating them less could help. 

Talk to your doctor about allergy testing.

5. POOR SLEEP. This just effs up so many things with your health 🤦🏾‍♀️ Ask your doctor if nothing seems to work.

6. FRICTION. Things rubbing against your skin like masks *worn for hours*, certain fabrics, beards rubbing against the face (that would be my trigger sadly 😩), etc can cause breakouts.

Creating a barrier between the item and your skin can help avoid friction. With masks worn for most of the day, apply a layer of petroleum jelly (plain Vaseline, Aquaphor, etc) on the face along where the mask rubs against the face.

7. CERTAIN MEDICATIONS. Obviously talk to your doctor about this, but understand they may think that the acne side effect is worth treating whatever condition you have.

🗣 It’s OK to NOT be all one color from head to toe.

Gotta run this back because summer is coming

Hyperpigmentation occurs after things like friction, ingrown hairs, irritation, etc and for some areas where the skin is thicker to facilitate movement ie knees, elbows, knuckles, toes.

Many of us are also born with areas that are different colors from the rest of our body. This is NORMAL.

👋🏿 Skin rubbing against skin can cause discoloration—this is why you notice discoloration in areas like in between the thighs and in folds of skin. Your clothing may also cause it—ie the shoulders from your bra straps or ankles from socks

👙 You may also notice discoloration in areas where you routinely remove hair: under the arms, bikini area, etc.

✨ Being one uniform color from head to toe is amazing, but you don’t have to have that to look amazing.

❌ Ok so how do you get rid of the discoloration?

🙏🏿 Body discoloration requires patience as it can take longer to fade than the face.

But things like…
✅ routine exfoliation (be gentle though)

✅ avoiding them boiling hot showers y’all seem to love (they dry out our already dry body skin and dryness can lead to hyperpigmentation)

✅ products that contain ingredients like niacinamide, retinol, kojic acid, licorice root, alpha arbutin, etc to help with fading

✅ pro treatments (peels, lasers, etc)

✅ and of course sunscreen

…can help treat it BUT—and this a big ole BUT—the discoloration will come back unless you avoid what caused it in the first place

Which can be difficult to avoid. Thighs gonna thigh unless you just stop walking 🤣 Chaffing creams and biker shorts can help decrease the skin rubbing against skin.

🚫 Less frequent hair removal in the case of the bikini and underarms can lessen discoloration there. Talk to a well-vetted skin of color pro about laser hair removal or electrolysis

Now while discoloration can be normal, some discoloration (ie on the neck) can be a sign of a medical issue. If it seems to come out of nowhere, changes shape, color or size, etc, TALK TO YOUR DOCTOR.

Who here still takes them boiling HOT showers? Some of y’all won’t quit so I’m Usher to your BS, you can let it burn 🔥 🔥🔥 But if you’re new here, here’s why you wanna turn the temp down 

(and notice I ain’t say bathe in COLD water)

Hot water zaps the skin of moisture—skin of color already suffers more from transepidermal water loss (basically means the skin doesn’t hold onto and loses the water/hydration it desperately needs—you can also look at it as the scientific term for ASHINESS 😝) To reiterate, hot water makes dry skin worse. 📝 

⚠️ And if you have a barrier imparing skin condition such as eczema, that hot water gonna do you in and make that ish go from like a 3 to a 20 on the DRYYYYYY scale.

🍂 Dry skin can also turn into other issues such as hyperpigmentation. 

✨Here’s what to do for healthy, GLOWING skin✨

✅ Turn the water temp down, you psycho

✅ While your skin is still a little damp from your shower, apply your moisturizer

✅ if you have particularly dry and/or sensitive skin, consider fragrance-free body washes/soaps and moisturizers. Fragrance can be a common trigger if you have very dry skin.

🥊 HOW TO FIGHT BACNE:

✅ Get out of sweaty clothes ASAP

✅ Be mindful of clothing or accessories that rub against the skin—that friction could cause acne. Look into lubricants like aquaphor, petroleum jelly, chub rub, deodorant sticks, etc to help prevent friction. Head to my Thigh Burn post on my Reel page for product recs

✅ Use a salicylic acid body wash (or spray) to help treat and prevent body acne

CLEARING DARK SPOTS ON THE BODY 🚫🍪 

✅ Consider switching to gentler body washes—maybe even look into fragrance-free washes if you have particularly dry and/or sensitive skin. Dryness can also lead to hyperpigmentation. See my Hot Showers Reel for recs.

✅ Ditch them hot a$$ showers. Hot water zaps skin of moisture and can dry out the skin making hyperpigmentation worse 🤦🏾‍♀️

✅ Use a dark spot treatment and consider a retinol body lotion on alternate nights (comment BACNE to have links sent to your DM)

✅ Don’t forget SUNSCREEN. Sun exposure can make both acne AND hyperpigmentation WORSE.

BUT THE BIGGEST THING? 
You gotta be ✨PATIENT✨ and ✨CONSISTENT✨

If you thought hyperpigmentation took a while to clear on the face, it can be even LONGER for the body. Be patient and consistent. 

Do what you can at home, but also consider getting treatments with a WELL-VETTED skin of color pro. They have things like peels, lasers, etc that can also help you get to your goals. Head to the PRO SKIN highlight on my page @stylenbeautydoc for info on how to find one near you.

✋🏿 READ ME ⚠️ Do you NEED all these steps? No. But if you like the extras and they don’t irritate your skin, this is the *general* order to apply them. Keep reading for an important hack if you think you have sensitive skin.

FAQs:

WHERE DOES MY ACNE TREATMENT GO?

Treatment products can often come in different forms. If it’s a toner (like the Paula’s Choice BHA toner), it goes in the toner step. If it’s a lotion or cream it goes before your moisturizer.

WHERE DOES MY RETINOID GO?

Retinoids can also come in different forms. If it’s a toner, it goes in the toner step. A lotion or cream before your moisturizer—BUT keep reading because there is an exception.

WHAT’S THE DEAL WITH THE SUNSCREEN?

Your sunscreen should always be your last step in your daytime routine. 

There is a thing going around that your sunscreen should go before your moisturizer because your skin needs to absorb your sunscreen—but that is WRONG, boo.

Moisturizer first, give it a few minutes, and then your sunscreen. I say wait a bit in between these particular steps because some sunscreen formulas can pill up causing the sunscreen to clump up in little beads. A lot of formulas won’t do this though.

You can also combine two steps by just using a moisturizing sunscreen. My simple daytime anti-aging routine post on my blog (link in bio @stylenbeautydoc) has sunscreen recommendations based on your skin type. Go there now to find your next sunscreen 🥰

WHAT WAS THE HACK, D?!?!

My bad. The hack is if you’re using a treatment product especially a retinoid, you can actually apply your moisturizer FIRST, THEN the treatment product and then moisturizer again. This is also called the sandwich method. It helps to mitigate irritation which can sometimes be an issue when you’re trying a new treatment product.

Texture (atrophic scars, deep wrinkles, etc). Your moisturizers and over the counter retinols do what they can. Sometimes you need a well-vetted skin pro who has RECEIPTS they know what they’re doing with skin of color to step in.

ECZEMA-PRONE SKIN TIPS (also good general tips for fall/winter skin):

🚿 Bathe in WARM *NOT* boiling hot water 🤦🏾‍♀️

Hot water dries the skin and can contribute to damaging the skin’s barrier. And if you have eczema, your skin barrier is already impaired

🧴🧤 Overhaul your body care

This time of year I often have to say goodbye to some of the products I can use in the summer (fragranced body washes, body scrubs, etc) and instead opt for gentle, fragrance-free options that soothe and protect my skin. Comment “RELIEF” to have product links sent to your DM or click the link in my bio.

⚠️ Exfoliate sparingly

Yes, I know some of y’all wanna be scrubbed within an inch of your life, but dry, eczema-prone skin is already impaired—exfoliating too often can cause more flare-ups (and you can wind up injuring your skin). 

So what do you do? Definitely skip the exfoliating when you have active flare-ups. Besides, so many things we do to our skin already count as exfoliation. Simply rubbing your hands against your skin counts as exfoliation.

When your barrier is healthy, limit exfoliating to 1-2 times a week & look into gentle exfoliants made for sensitive skin—maybe even the types made for your face

‼️ Avoid itchy fabrics
Some wools & knits can further irritate the skin—try to avoid these or if you do wear them, consider layering something silk or satin underneath to protect your skin.

💦 Use a humidifier & limit indoor heating use—heat (and even AC) can be very drying on the skin. I am notorious for layering up instead of cranking the heat up

So while you might want to limit eating greasy foods for overall health reasons, greasy foods DON’T make your skin oilier.

Gentle cleansing should be part of your healthy skincare routine BUT overdoing it can actually leave the skin more susceptible to bacteria and UVA and UVB rays—aka you can make your acne worse AND could possibly introduce additional issues. 

I know some of y’all like to scrub within an inch of your skin’s life BUT this is hustling backwards. You risk damaging your skin’s barrier when you over-cleanse or over-exfoliate.

 When your skin barrier is damaged, your skin can’t function as it should—this could lead to inflammation which can result in excessive dryness, hyperpigmentation, etc. AND that mess hurts—like “even just splashing your face with water stings” hurts.

We live in a DIY world, but if you (or a loved one) are not able to handle your acne at home, contact a dermatology professional. For our unique skin tones, look for one who specializes in skin of color.  Check out AcneHormones.com for more info.

⚠️ ☀️ DO RETINOIDS MAKE SKIN MORE SENSITIVE TO THE SUN? 🤔
Not exactly. When you first start a retinoid, your skin may peel and become sensitive—at which point chilling up in the sun will do you ZERO favors, HOWEVER retinoids don’t make the skin more sensitive to the sun. You always want to wear sunscreen regardless, but since retinoids help with some of the damage caused by the sun, you don’t want to go out sunscreenless and undo all the work it did the night before. 

Also, some retinoids can degrade in the sun so they shouldn’t be used during the day. However, it depends on the formula. There are some that can be used during the day. Folow the directions on your product.
